03863nam a2200541Ia 9780791486351DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780791486351  a(DE-B1597)681787  a(OCoLC)1428235215  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJA66b.F685 2004 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a327.1/011 aFreyberg-Inan, Annette, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Moves Man :bThe Realist Theory of International Relations and Its Judgment of Human Nature /cAnnette Freyberg-Inan. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (272 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series in Global Politics00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tWhat Moves Man? An Analysis of the Realist Psychology -- tThe Roots of Realism -- tRealism Goes Modern -- tRealism Today -- tRealist Man through the Ages: A Synopsis -- tSunglasses at Night: A Critique of the Realist Psychology -- tWhat Is Wrong with the Realist Psychology? -- tThe Effects of the Realist Bias -- tA Self-Fulfilling Prophesy? -- tConclusion: Great Debates and Small Suggestions -- tBiographical Notes on Authors of Classical Realism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tSuny series in Global Politics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe realist theory of international relations is based on a particularly gloomy set of assumptions about universal human motives. Believing people to be essentially asocial, selfish, and untrustworthy, realism counsels a politics of distrust and competition in the international arena. What Moves Man subjects realism to a broad and deep critique. Freyberg-Inan argues, first, that realist psychology is incomplete and suffers from a pessimistic bias. Second, she explains how this bias systematically undermines both realist scholarship and efforts to promote international cooperation and peace. Third, she argues that realism's bias has a tendency to function as a self-fulfilling prophecy: it nurtures and promotes the very behaviors it assumes predominate human nature. Freyberg-Inan concludes by suggesting how a broader and more complex view of human motivation would deliver more complete explanations of international behavior, reduce the risk of bias, and better promote practical progress in the conduct of international affairs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInternational relations. 0aPolitical realism. 0aPolitical science. 0aRealismxPolitical aspects. 4aPolitics and Law : International Relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aRosenau, James N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791486351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791486351/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles